snippet.textDisplay: One of the best songs I have ever heard, such soulful voices and excellent background score makes this song purely mystic. And guys, forget India and Pakistan rivalry for heaven sake. We were one country before and all these songs transcend the history of our continent, it doesn't belong to either India or Pakistan, it's a shared heritage. Be proud of it and don't fight with each other. The song is sung for Hazrat Nizamuddin and in between also exalts Lord Krishna (Shyam). Back then sufi and bhakti era saints embraced each other's religions and created soulful songs. So, please enjoy and stay united by music. Please don't have a petty fight.

snippet.textDisplay:
Its been 2 days since I heard this for the first time (IKR I must have been living under a rock LOL) and I have heard it for about 40 times since. As good as Atif and Momina are in Tajdar-e-Haram and Afreen ... this is beyond anything I have ever heard. It's from another world, really. And both have 60 million + views, while this has less than 10m as I write this. I think this is what is wrong with the world today that we run after aesthetic beauty rather than actual beauty which is beyond skin deep. In other words, we run after material gains rather than spirituality and do not stop and see what is good in life and how we can help others. It is easier to fight and blame others (like Pak/India) for our ills rather than help each other out and accepting each other for who we are. (damn, this song has turned me into a philosopher of sorts)
One more thing, while Momina plays 2nd fiddle to RFAK in Afreen, here RFAK is second fiddle to Abida Parveen. Taking nothing away from RFAK, who is hands down the best Sufi/Qawal in the world at the moment, Abida Parveen is from another planet. I have never really listened to her that often before, and I question myself for that after listening to her here. It's like comparing Messi and Ronaldo TBH (Abida Parveen=Messi here, just to be clear). And I think she might even be more divine than the great Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan (please don't hate me for saying this), if it were not for the fact that she was a woman, she might have gotten more acclaim. I think it is time that we appreciate our living legends more than repenting over the legends who are no longer with us. Peace!
